It sounds like you're running into a common issue when setting up Firebase in a web project, particularly with managing different versions of the Firebase JavaScript SDK. The error Uncaught Error: Service firestore is not available often points directly to these version conflicts in your importmap . Don't worry, we can get this sorted out!
Here's a step-by-step guide to resolve the Firebase SDK version conflict and ensure Firestore is available:
Step 1: Unify Firebase SDK Versions in index.html The core problem is that your importmap is trying to load different versions of Firebase. You need to ensure all Firebase-related imports refer to a single, consistent version.
Locate your index.html file.
Find the <script type="importmap"> block.
Remove the wildcard entry: "firebase/": "https://esm.sh/firebase@^12.6.0/"
Ensure all specific Firebase module imports point to the same version. For example, if you want to use version 10.12.2 , your importmap should look something like this:
    <script type="importmap">
      {
        "imports": {
          "firebase/app": "https://esm.sh/firebase@10.12.2/app",
          "firebase/firestore": "https://esm.sh/firebase@10.12.2/firestore",
          "firebase/storage": "https://esm.sh/firebase@10.12.2/storage",
          // Add other Firebase modules here, all using @10.12.2
          // If you need more recent features, pick a single, later version for all of them.
        }
      }
    </script>
    ```
Expand
Step 2: Clean and Reinstall Dependencies (if using npm/yarn) If you're managing your project with npm or yarn (even in a Google AI Studio environment that might have a similar setup), conflicting versions can persist. This step helps ensure a clean installation.
Delete your node_modules directory.
Delete your package-lock.json (for npm) or yarn.lock (for yarn) file.
Run npm install or yarn install to reinstall dependencies.
(Optional but recommended): Use npm ls firebase --all to verify that no conflicting firebase module versions are being pulled in by other packages.
Step 3: Verify Firebase Initialization in firebaseService.ts Ensure your firebaseService.ts file correctly initializes Firebase and Firestore using the modular SDK.
Confirm you are importing initializeApp from firebase/app and getFirestore from firebase/firestore .
Your initialization code should resemble this:
    import { initializeApp } from 'firebase/app';
    import { getFirestore } from 'firebase/firestore'; // Assuming 'firebase/firestore' is in your importmap

    const firebaseConfig = {
      // Your Firebase project configuration
    };

    const app = initializeApp(firebaseConfig);
    export const firestore = getFirestore(app);
    ```
Expand
Step 4: Review for CJS/ESM Conflicts (if issues persist) If the problem continues, consider if you're mixing CommonJS ( require ) and ES Modules ( import ) statements, which can lead to multiple, incompatible instances of the Firebase SDK.
Ensure consistent use of import statements throughout your project for Firebase modules.
Check your bundler's configuration (if you're using one) for any settings that might cause module resolution issues.
By carefully following these steps, you should be able to resolve the firestore is not available error by ensuring a consistent Firebase SDK version across your application.
